================================================================================
 Deposit Calculator — isolated debug: raw InterestRateUploadLocalService call
================================================================================
Purpose: isolate the service call from all the JSON-building/null-guard logic
in `calculator` (section 7), to find out exactly where the "rate has
evaluated to null or missing" error is really coming from. Fully static
inputs — nothing computed, nothing looped over customerCategories. Every
single field access is individually guarded with its own <#if x??> so that
even if one specific property is the actual problem, it gets reported
instead of crashing the whole render.

Static test values confirmed correct: true, "2", "South Africa", "Normal".

Revision note: the previous version of this file asserted `testRates`
directly from the method call, then checked `testRates??` on separate
lines before dereferencing `?size`/`?is_sequence` on it. That still hit
"testRates has evaluated to null or missing" at the ${testRates?size} call —
*inside* the <#if testRates??> guard that should have prevented it ever
running. `??`/`!` only catch a value being null; they cannot catch a Java
exception being thrown during evaluation, and a guarded expression still
failing behind its own guard is a strong signal this is a thrown exception
being surfaced through FreeMarker's generic "null or missing" message
rather than an actual null value. Applying `!` directly at the point of
assignment (see rawTestRates/testRates split below) removes the ambiguity
either way: if the *raw* call still throws, the exception surfaces exactly
at the <#assign rawTestRates = ...> line instead of somewhere downstream
behind a guard that looked like it should have worked.

How to use:
  1. Swap this in as your fragment's index.html content temporarily (in
     place of the full calculator).
  2. Publish the fragment and test on an ACTUAL PAGE, not just the Fragment
     Editor's Draft preview panel — the last screenshot showed this running
     in the unpublished Draft preview, which may execute FTL in a more
     restricted context than a real page render (this hasn't been ruled out
     yet and is now the most likely remaining variable).
  3. If it still fails, check the server log (SystemOut/catalina.out) for
     the same timestamp — Liferay typically logs the full Java stack trace
     for a template-render failure server-side even when the on-screen
     message is FreeMarker's generic summary. That trace will show the real
     exception type/cause, which the on-screen FTL error can't.
  4. Report back exactly what renders: the "Service located"/"Raw result
     exists"/"Result size" lines, and each <li> row underneath.

--- index.html (temporary, replaces the full calculator while debugging) ---
<div class="dc-debug">
	<h3>Debug: Raw Service Call Test</h3>

	<#assign interestRateUploadLocalService = serviceLocator.findService("com.sbi.core.service.service.InterestRateUploadLocalService")>
	<p>Service located: <#if interestRateUploadLocalService??>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>

	<#-- Raw, unguarded assign on purpose: if the call itself throws, the
	     error now points exactly here instead of somewhere downstream
	     behind a guard that looked correct. -->
	<#assign rawTestRates = interestRateUploadLocalService.findByIsActiveStatusCountryNCategory(true, "2", "South Africa", "Normal")>
	<p>Raw result exists (not null): <#if rawTestRates??>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>

	<#-- From here on, testRates can never be null — ![] guarantees an
	     empty sequence instead, so every downstream ?size/?is_sequence/
	     <#list> below is unconditionally safe regardless of what the raw
	     call returned. -->
	<#assign testRates = rawTestRates![]>
	<p>Result is a sequence: <#if testRates?is_sequence>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>
	<p>Result size: ${testRates?size}</p>

	<ul>
		<#list testRates as rate>
			<li>
				Index ${rate_index}:
				<#if !rate??>
					rate is NULL
				<#else>
					rate exists |
					category=<#if rate.category??>${rate.category}<#else>[category missing]</#if> |
					interestType=<#if rate.interestType??>${rate.interestType}<#else>[interestType missing]</#if> |
					interestRate=<#if rate.interestRate??>${rate.interestRate}<#else>[interestRate missing]</#if> |
					status=<#if rate.status??>${rate.status}<#else>[status missing]</#if>
				</#if>
			</li>
		</#list>
	</ul>
</div>

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What each outcome would tell us
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- "Service located: NO"
    serviceLocator.findService(...) itself isn't resolving the interface —
    wrong fully-qualified interface name, module not actually deployed with
    that package path, or serviceLocator is restricted/unavailable in this
    execution context (Fragment preview sandbox vs. real page render).

- The error now appears at the <#assign rawTestRates = ...> line itself
    Confirms this is a thrown Java exception, not a null value — check the
    server log at this timestamp for the real stack trace. Common causes:
    a bug in findByIsActiveNStatusNCountryNCategory's underlying SQL/finder,
    a param-count/type mismatch against what's actually deployed, or the
    method not existing yet on the deployed LocalService (Service Builder
    not rerun after adding it).

- "Raw result exists: NO" but no exception thrown
    findByIsActiveStatusCountryNCategory returned Java null instead of an
    empty list for this query — a persistence-layer bug worth fixing at the
    source (the finder should return an empty List, never null). Harmless
    here since testRates![] catches it, but still worth fixing upstream.

- "Result size: 0"
    The query ran fine but nothing matches isActive=true, status="2",
    country="South Africa", category="Normal" — check the seeded data
    matches those exact values (case-sensitivity included).

- "rate is NULL" on some index
    Confirms the underlying List really does contain a null element —
    a genuine bug in findByIsActiveNStatusNCountryNCategory (or the SQL/
    finder it delegates to), independent of anything in the fragment's FTL.

- A specific field reported "[xxx missing]" while others show real values
    rate itself is fine; that one column is null for that row (or the
    getter name doesn't match what's assumed here) — narrows the fix to
    that column specifically rather than the whole object.

- Everything above renders fine on a published page but failed in the
  Fragment Editor's Draft preview
    Confirms the preview sandbox is the actual culprit — treat Draft
    preview errors on serviceLocator-backed fragments as unreliable going
    forward and always verify against a published page instead.
